	where $M(r)$ is the cumulated baryonic mass under the radius $r$ and $v_\mathrm{c}(r)$ the circular velocity at the same radius. This equation is precise in the modified inertia theories \citep{milg94} and only approximate in the modified gravity theories \citep{brada95} but it gets precise for large radii to reproduce the universal {Eq.~\ref{eq:{btfr}}}. The rotation curves calculated from the distribution of the baryonic matter by this way reproduce even small details on the observed rotational curves for many galaxies (see examples in \citealp{famaey12} and {Fig.~\ref{fig:{rc}}}).

